        <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Ultimate Guide and Cheatsheet to Custom Songs on Suno AI (Latest Version: v4.5, as of August 2025)</h1>
        <p>Suno AI is a powerful tool for generating original music from text prompts, allowing anyone to create full songs with lyrics, vocals, and instrumentation. As of v4.5 (released in May 2025), Suno has significantly improved prompt adherence, voice quality, genre mashups, and song length (up to 8 minutes). It supports free access with daily credits (limited to approximately 10 songs per day on v3.5 or v4 models) and paid plans (Pro or Plus) for unlimited generations, access to v4.5, stems, editing tools, and more. You can use it via suno.com, the mobile app, or integrations.</p>
        <p>This guide builds on community resources like the LoftwahFM Suno Playbook, incorporating updates from official releases, user tips from Reddit and X, and prompting best practices. It focuses on custom mode for maximum control, where you input lyrics and styles. For the easiest start, use simple mode: just describe your song (for example, "uplifting pop track about summer love") and let Suno generate everything.</p>

        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6">1. Quick Start: Generating Your First Custom Song</h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-3">
          <li>
            <strong>Pick a Base Style</strong>: Start simple to avoid overwhelming the AI. Reliable bases include:
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 mt-2 space-y-1">
              <li>Boom bap + nylon guitar (simple, singable hip hop or rock blend).</li>
              <li>Piano ballad (intimate, clean vocals).</li>
              <li>Nu-groove (hip hop times rock grit + chant).</li>
              <li>DnB song (half-time verse then double-time drop).</li>
              <li>New in v4.5: Genre mashups like "punk rock with neosoul" or "EDM folk" for cohesive hybrids.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Set a Header Line</strong>: At the top of your prompt, define tempo, key, vibe, and 3 to 6 instruments. This anchors the AI.
            <div class="mt-2"><code class="inline-block bg-black border border-white px-2 py-1 text-xs">[Intro - 92 BPM, A minor; half-sung vocals; sub bass, muted guitar, crisp snare, sparse keys, vinyl crackle]</code></div>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Write Lyrics</strong>: Keep lines short (4 to 8 words) and singable. Use section tags for structure. Repeat hooks exactly for catchiness.</li>
          <li><strong>Add Style and Tags</strong>: Describe genre, mood, and vocals in a separate field or inline. Use v4.5's Prompt Enhancement Helper: input rough tags (for example, "lofi chill female vocals"), select Enhance, and get a refined prompt.</li>
          <li><strong>Generate and Refine</strong>: Select Create for two versions. Use thumbs up or down to train the AI. Extend songs up to 8 minutes, remix, or apply covers or personas for voice or style tweaks.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="mt-2"><strong>Golden Rules (Updated for v4.5)</strong>:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Fewer words, fewer instruments, more intent: avoid over-specifying to prevent muddy mixes. Aim for 3 to 6 key elements.</li>
          <li>v4.5 is smarter: better interpretation of moods (for example, "nostalgic uplifting tones") and complex sounds (for example, "leaf textures in melodic whistling").</li>
          <li>Avoid artist names: use style descriptors instead (for example, "80s pop with danceable beats").</li>
          <li>Test in pieces: generate verses or choruses separately, then extend or remix.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6">2. Prompt Structure and Best Practices</h2>
        <p>Suno prompts have two main parts: <strong>Style Description</strong> (genre, mood, instruments) and <strong>Lyrics</strong> (structured with tags). v4.5 adheres better to details, reducing hallucinations like rapping over melodic requests.</p>
        <p class="mt-2"><strong>Basic Prompt Format</strong>:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Style: "Genre, mood, key elements. Vocal style."</li>
          <li>Lyrics: use [tags] for sections, vocals, and effects.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-2"><strong>Components for Effective Prompts</strong>:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li><strong>Genre or Style</strong>: broad (pop) or specific (synthwave). Mashups work well in v4.5 (for example, "jazz house with gregorian chant").</li>
          <li><strong>Mood or Emotion</strong>: uplifting, melancholic, gritty. Pair with actions (for example, "punchy drums building tension").</li>
          <li><strong>Tempo and Key</strong>: hip hop 80 to 95 BPM; house 120 to 128 BPM; DnB 170 to 175 BPM. Minor feels moody; major feels bright. Use a bridge key lift for energy.</li>
          <li><strong>Instruments</strong>: 3 to 6 maximum (for example, sub bass, reese bass for DnB). Specify playing style (for example, palm-muted guitar).</li>
          <li><strong>Vocals</strong>: half-sung, chant hook, stacked harmonies. v4.5 supports emotional range (vibrato, whispers).</li>
          <li><strong>Production</strong>: glossy mix, lo-fi crackle, side-chained bass.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-2"><strong>Advanced Tips</strong>:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
          <li>Use metatags inline for control: [beat drop], [riser]. Place sparingly like seasoning.</li>
          <li>v4.5 sliders: adjust Weirdness (creativity), Structure (adherence to tags), Reference Driven (match uploaded audio).</li>
          <li>Upload audio: extend from your riffs or tracks (up to 8 minutes). Use stems to extract vocals or drums for remixing.</li>
          <li>Personas or covers: beta feature to replicate vocals from existing tracks. Combine with remixes (for example, rock to house).</li>
        </ul>

